WEBVTT

00:11.330 --> 00:16.575
Welcome to Baria Temple International Church's Podcast.

00:16.595 --> 00:23.101
I am your host Timothy, and we're here together on this beautiful day to hear from God.

00:24.382 --> 00:33.351
Today, we're fortunate to have our beloved pastor, Michael Gonzalez, with us who will be sharing God's word.

00:34.612 --> 00:40.658
So let's all prepare ourselves to receive what God has in store for us today.

00:42.018 --> 00:43.921
Let's begin.

00:43.941 --> 00:46.865
So that being said, I need to do something a little bit different.

00:46.985 --> 00:50.490
I need a couple of ushers to come, if you would.

00:51.411 --> 00:54.095
On the front row, there's a great big stack of paper.

00:54.436 --> 00:57.119
And I need each person to take one sheet of paper.

00:57.139 --> 01:03.568
So ushers, if you don't mind, to pass those out while I'm preaching, I'm just going to let you take care of that while we go.

01:03.969 --> 01:05.211
But just hold on to it.

01:05.311 --> 01:06.833
It'll be for later in the service.

01:06.913 --> 01:10.418
But ushers, if you'll take care of that now, I would greatly appreciate it.

01:10.690 --> 01:15.698
So again, we have been exploring in our series, in our messages.

01:16.179 --> 01:19.905
We have been working on our series called We Are.

01:20.727 --> 01:25.354
And we are AG, I'm gonna get through this real quick, because we have covered this lots.

01:25.875 --> 01:27.358
We are AG church members.

01:28.680 --> 01:32.867
We are AG church members who offer hope and healing in our community.

01:33.147 --> 01:34.570
And we're dialing this down.

01:34.590 --> 01:37.074
This is still part of the hope and healing.

01:37.538 --> 01:49.913
But we're going to tile it down to something a bit more specific for this sub-series is we want to be a church that understands what it is to be the body of Christ.

01:50.293 --> 01:58.103
What it is to be a church that offers hope and healing and ultimately by being good neighbors.

01:58.523 --> 02:03.049
Knowing how to exist as Christians in a lost and dying world.

02:03.790 --> 02:06.413
How to be a Christian in a foreign land.

02:06.433 --> 02:07.314
We are

02:07.650 --> 02:16.606
Okay, if any of you are not aware, we had two last weekend, Petra, the Christian rock band was here in concert at Berea Temple.

02:16.967 --> 02:19.131
One of their songs is called, Not of This World.

02:19.211 --> 02:22.597
It's the first song that I, that's what made me fall in love with them.

02:22.617 --> 02:26.485
And one of the lines in that song is, we are strangers.

02:27.006 --> 02:28.689
We are not of this world.

02:29.250 --> 02:31.634
We are strangers in a foreign land.

02:32.450 --> 02:33.652
And that is who we are.

02:33.692 --> 02:45.334
And so that's why we're covering this series today, that we are good neighbors in a foreign land talking to foreign people who know nothing of our Jesus.

02:46.717 --> 02:53.810
And so I have a question I want to start out with is how many times we found ourselves talking about love?

02:54.146 --> 02:56.990
We do it almost every February in some form or fashion.

02:57.331 --> 02:58.893
We talk about Jesus' love.

02:58.913 --> 03:03.099
We talk about the love of God, the love of the Father, the love of the Holy Spirit.

03:03.139 --> 03:05.102
We talk about loving our spouses.

03:05.182 --> 03:07.105
We talk about all kinds of love.

03:07.125 --> 03:07.967
We preach about it.

03:08.227 --> 03:10.410
We even post on social media about it.

03:10.771 --> 03:12.073
Oh, what a cute little puppy.

03:12.113 --> 03:13.495
Here's a picture of my baby.

03:13.835 --> 03:14.917
I love tacos.

03:15.137 --> 03:15.858
Amen, right?

03:16.279 --> 03:16.880
Okay.

03:16.980 --> 03:21.106
So whatever it is we'd like to talk about love.

03:22.338 --> 03:32.374
And love is a central theme to our faith when it comes to practicing love in our everyday lives, especially towards those living closest to us.

03:33.236 --> 03:35.159
We very often fall short.

03:36.281 --> 03:38.104
It's easy to love our friends.

03:38.184 --> 03:41.630
It's easy to love those that we choose to be around.

03:43.593 --> 03:49.202
And it's sometimes even easy to love strangers we meet during outreach events.

03:49.890 --> 03:52.935
We hear their story and we go, oh, let me tell you about Jesus.

03:53.416 --> 03:54.097
And that's nice.

03:54.157 --> 03:54.818
That's wonderful.

03:54.838 --> 03:58.084
It makes us feel good because we've made a personal connection.

04:00.588 --> 04:04.555
But what about people who live right next door?

04:05.477 --> 04:09.544
The people we share a wall if you live in an apartment or if you live in a duplex.

04:09.744 --> 04:13.330
The people that we share a fence with if you live in a house or even just

04:13.538 --> 04:23.771
If you don't have a fence, you share the block with this circle, square, rectangle, whatever shape yours is, block of ground, and we call them our neighbors.

04:24.412 --> 04:30.459
Did you know that research shows that over 30% of people don't know their neighbors?

04:31.360 --> 04:32.682
They don't know their neighbors' names.

04:33.984 --> 04:35.986
They don't know anything about them.

04:37.474 --> 04:47.447
And it's 30% in urban and suburban areas, and the number increases in rural areas just simply due to distance and fewer community building opportunities.

04:47.747 --> 04:52.233
However, here in St. Louis, we have a great opportunity to know our neighbors.

04:53.215 --> 05:01.906
There's always an event happening all the time, whether it's a farmer's market, it's a craft fair, a cultural fair, block parties, whatever the list goes on.

05:02.946 --> 05:11.936
And in St. Louis, we have the beautifully unique makeup of our city where we have neighborhoods.

05:12.397 --> 05:13.798
We are in Compton Heights.

05:14.219 --> 05:22.648
Some of you live in Shaw or some other neighborhood that has a name and there is a community identity built around it.

05:22.708 --> 05:26.672
Some of them are good, some of them are less than good.

05:27.333 --> 05:28.114
We'll leave it at that.

05:29.698 --> 05:36.679
But each one of us is part of a community that we get to call our neighbors.

05:39.387 --> 05:41.734
See, we have the opportunity in St. Louis to live.

05:42.115 --> 05:44.402
A lot of our houses are very close together.

05:44.514 --> 05:48.922
Matter of fact, some of our houses, we couldn't get a slip of paper between them, but there is a gap.

05:49.363 --> 06:00.224
I was driving down one street one day and I happened to catch light between two of the buildings and I went, oh, they're not physically connected, but there's probably no more than an inch gap between those two buildings.

06:02.508 --> 06:05.554
And we have the opportunity to not be a statistic.

06:07.362 --> 06:07.863
tell you a story.

06:07.903 --> 06:14.414
There was a pastor named Mark who wanted to reach his local community in some kind of meaningful way.

06:14.715 --> 06:20.184
And he organized a huge church event, a family fun day with games, food, live music.

06:20.485 --> 06:28.258
Mark and his ministry team worked tirelessly advertising it throughout town, sending out flyers, spreading the word on social media.

06:28.639 --> 06:32.946
And on the day of the event, they set up everything perfectly.

06:33.602 --> 06:35.244
Couldn't have been a better day.

06:35.545 --> 06:36.827
The weather was wonderful.

06:37.067 --> 06:38.249
The sun was shining.

06:38.509 --> 06:41.593
The food was all hot and ready to go.

06:41.894 --> 06:43.376
The games were put in place.

06:43.636 --> 06:48.863
But as the hours passed, only a handful of people showed up.

06:50.265 --> 06:51.447
Pastor Mark was disappointed.

06:53.430 --> 06:56.634
Later that day, he was driving home and he was feeling disappointed.

06:56.955 --> 07:02.162
He passed by a local park and saw the park was packed with families.

07:02.242 --> 07:07.411
kids playing, parents chatting, and people enjoying the beautiful afternoon together.

07:08.473 --> 07:09.454
And that's when it hit him.

07:11.097 --> 07:20.092
While he had been focused on drawing people to his church event, the community was already gathering regularly at the park.

07:20.112 --> 07:28.306
And he realized that instead of trying to bring people into the church, maybe he should take the church to where the people already are.

07:30.978 --> 07:35.084
It's just an illustration, it's just a, I would likely guess a made up story.

07:37.047 --> 07:56.594
But it's one that reminds us that sometimes we work hard on big plans, big events, hoping to draw people in and show Christ's love, but we simply miss the opportunities that are right in front of us.

07:57.602 --> 08:01.888
The people we want to reach are often already gathering in our communities.

08:02.769 --> 08:05.693
We just need to notice them and meet them where they are.

08:06.955 --> 08:08.657
Notice the word meet.

08:09.779 --> 08:10.940
It doesn't say invade.

08:12.382 --> 08:23.337
So it doesn't mean we gather as a church and we march over here to the park and start shoving tracks in people's faces, pounding our Bibles.

08:25.040 --> 08:26.642
It says we meet them where they are.

08:27.938 --> 08:29.000
What do I mean by that?

08:29.961 --> 08:34.649
So I was asked when I very first got here, I was asked about evangelism.

08:35.971 --> 08:44.825
And we've been, we've done some of those big outreaches, and we've done some of those medium-sized outreaches, and we've had it where only a few people showed up, but guess what?

08:44.885 --> 08:46.688
We met neighbors, that's a good thing.

08:49.352 --> 08:53.759
But I am a proponent of lifestyle evangelism.

08:54.240 --> 08:55.442
What do I mean by that?

08:56.354 --> 09:00.478
They will know you are Christians by your love, one for another.

09:02.039 --> 09:04.021
They will know that you are my disciples.

09:06.924 --> 09:07.124
How?

09:08.285 --> 09:09.867
But how we interact with each other.

09:13.370 --> 09:19.897
The fruits of the Spirit operating in us is the greatest form of evangelism that we can have.

09:21.838 --> 09:25.522
So coming to church on Sunday and you listen, you hear me harp on this all the time.

09:25.826 --> 09:32.974
Coming to church on Sunday, but going to the bar on Saturday, not lifestyle evangelism.

09:34.035 --> 09:40.563
Coming to church on Sunday and standing up on the platform, I know nothing about anybody that's up here, so I'm not picking on anybody.

09:41.544 --> 09:53.778
But standing up on the platform, but doing something that's ungodly during the week, something that is not in line with your faith, not evangelism.

09:55.010 --> 09:57.214
We're doing one of two things throughout the week.

09:57.875 --> 10:02.823
We're either drawing people closer to Christ through our lives or repelling people farther away.

10:03.124 --> 10:06.229
When they look at our lives, they either say, I want to be more like that.

10:06.830 --> 10:08.333
I want to be more like that Jesus.

10:08.914 --> 10:10.917
Or they say, I want nothing to do with that.

10:12.540 --> 10:16.306
They're fake, they're mean, they're rude, they're crude, they, whatever it may be.

10:19.650 --> 10:27.378
We need to meet people where they are and we need to let our light show shine before men that they know we are His disciples.

10:32.442 --> 10:40.651
See our efforts to show love and to be impactful in our events, to host community outreaches, to spread the gospel.

10:41.531 --> 10:48.338
These are all wonderful, but sometimes we overlook the obvious places where we can connect with other places.

10:51.266 --> 10:55.453
There are God places in our neighborhoods.

10:57.717 --> 10:59.059
Notice I said God not good.

11:00.101 --> 11:17.490
There are God places in our neighborhoods, parks, the daily routines of life, but we're not paying attention and we might miss those chances to share love in a real and meaningful way.

11:17.890 --> 11:18.631
Starbucks.

11:18.691 --> 11:23.939
I've already told you the story about me being called the Bible guy on the bus when I had to read for college.

11:24.780 --> 11:37.580
And it was just simply, I did nothing specifically outreach driven, but I had my Bible because I had an assignment and I was dumb enough to take New Testament, survey and Old Testament survey in the same semester.

11:38.762 --> 11:41.746
And I had to read the entire Bible in about 90 days.

11:44.738 --> 11:45.659
And so what did I do?

11:45.939 --> 11:49.062
I had, I worked clear across town and I rode the bus back and forth.

11:49.082 --> 11:52.045
Well, I was reading, reading, reading people took notice.

11:52.466 --> 11:54.708
That's just my life, lifestyle.

11:56.029 --> 12:01.975
How can we put that kind because we're missing the opportunities when we don't?

12:02.356 --> 12:12.786
If everything is always a scripted challenge, then we might be missing the regular divine appointments that God has placed in front of us.

12:14.370 --> 12:25.965
And while big outreaches and big events and all of those things are wonderful, they can't substitute the day-to-day relationship that Jesus calls us to have with His people.

12:26.245 --> 12:28.488
Look at Luke chapter 16 and verse 10.

12:29.829 --> 12:33.154
It says, if you're faithful in little things, you'll be faithful in large ones.

12:33.434 --> 12:38.160
But if you're dishonest in little things, you won't be honest with greater responsibilities.

12:39.482 --> 12:41.124
How do we apply that to evangelism?

12:42.505 --> 12:43.026
Simple.

12:44.226 --> 12:45.388
God says, look, go down.

12:45.448 --> 12:48.154
If you're a Starbucks person, I won't judge you.

12:48.174 --> 12:50.559
Yes, I'm going to judge you, but it's okay.

12:50.579 --> 12:53.284
If you're a Starbucks person, go down and sit and have your morning coffee.

12:55.949 --> 12:59.616
Look for divine opportunities, divine appointments.

12:59.636 --> 13:04.466
Have conversations, the same person sitting in the same seat every day.

13:06.786 --> 13:10.471
Take an opportunity to reach out or to strike up a conversation.

13:10.771 --> 13:18.300
And the way this passage applies is if you're not willing to have just a basic old normal, and again, I'm out of home, hey brother, do you know Jesus?

13:20.103 --> 13:21.284
But simply, hey, how are you?

13:21.584 --> 13:29.414
I noticed you were in here every day this last week, everything going okay, or their head is down and normally they're clacking away right in their next great novel, right?

13:29.554 --> 13:31.296
Because that's what everybody at Starbucks is doing.

13:33.239 --> 13:35.762
And all of a sudden they come in and their laptop is closed,

13:36.418 --> 13:37.359
Their head is down.

13:40.504 --> 13:43.147
Hey, I see you in here all the time.

13:45.010 --> 13:51.018
You look way different today than you did yesterday and the other days, are you okay?

13:51.038 --> 13:53.301
Well, you know, I'm really going through, but guess what?

13:53.381 --> 13:53.962
Window open.

13:54.763 --> 13:55.985
Conversation can happen.

13:56.746 --> 13:58.448
That's the small things.

13:58.648 --> 14:02.994
That's the regular everyday things that God wants us to be doing.

14:03.426 --> 14:13.119
It's great to come to church and say, we're having an outreach and I'm gonna be the prayer tent person or I'm gonna be the guest check-in person or I'm gonna be the hot dog person.

14:13.359 --> 14:14.461
Those are all wonderful.

14:17.224 --> 14:18.065
What about the little ones?

14:18.686 --> 14:19.627
What about the little things?

14:22.531 --> 14:27.698
Today I wanna challenge us to take the great commandment

14:27.778 --> 14:32.364
Seriously, we talked about this last time last week of a great commandment versus the great commission.

14:32.705 --> 14:42.838
And I want us to take it seriously, not just as a spiritual ideology, but as a practical everyday personal, say the word personal, personal mission.

14:44.360 --> 14:49.867
Jesus told us to love our neighbors as ourselves and that commandment was meant to be taken literally.

14:50.107 --> 14:52.050
What would happen if we stopped

14:52.194 --> 14:59.022
thinking of neighbor as a metaphor, as a construct for anyone and everyone in need.

14:59.383 --> 15:05.330
So the guy down begging at the corner over here or the homeless camp or whatever it may be.

15:07.172 --> 15:12.138
But we started thinking about it as a literal person living next door.

15:12.879 --> 15:18.706
The actual person that lives in the house, the apartment, the duplex next door to you.

15:20.482 --> 15:43.144
How would our lives change and how would our communities change if you, as the center of your little circle of houses, took loving your neighbor the great commandments seriously and became an embassy for heaven in your neighborhood.

15:44.825 --> 15:49.970
And you became an ambassador for the greatest king that has ever been known.

15:52.514 --> 15:56.439
And you begin to be his mouthpiece in your neighborhood.

15:59.323 --> 16:05.010
So today, if you're a note taker, our sermon title today is taking the great commandment seriously.

16:07.714 --> 16:14.162
We're going to break down three key areas where we can live out the commandments more effectively.

16:14.754 --> 16:18.880
First, we need to understand who our neighbors are, not just in theory, but in reality.

16:18.920 --> 16:24.748
Second, we need to confront and overcome the barriers that keep us from loving them as we should.

16:24.788 --> 16:31.377
And finally, we'll look at how to move from talking about love to actually practicing it in everyday lives.

16:31.617 --> 16:37.705
But I want us to look first at what Jesus' words are in Matthew 22, verses 37 to 40.

16:37.866 --> 16:41.010
Matthew 22, verses 37 to 40.

16:41.282 --> 16:47.910
This is what it says, it says, Jesus replied, you must love you the Lord your God with all of your heart, all your soul and all of your mind.

16:48.371 --> 16:50.394
This is the first and greatest commandment.

16:50.694 --> 16:52.416
The second is equally important.

16:52.656 --> 16:54.278
Love your neighbor as yourself.

16:54.699 --> 17:00.747
The entire law and all the demands of the prophets are based on these two commandments.

17:02.068 --> 17:03.410
This is the great commandment.

17:06.370 --> 17:07.912
So now I want us to dig in with this.

17:07.953 --> 17:09.635
This is kind of our foundation.

17:09.735 --> 17:15.565
Again, this is probably going to be a bulk of our foundation when we talk about being good neighbors.

17:16.286 --> 17:20.953
First thing is that we are called to love our literal neighbors.

17:23.577 --> 17:24.018
Mark,

17:24.322 --> 17:31.155
Chapter 12 and verse 30 and 31 is basically a restatement of the Matthew passage, the great commandment.

17:31.376 --> 17:37.948
So this is how Mark says it and he says, and you must love the Lord your God with all of your heart, all of your soul, all of your mind and all of your strength.

17:38.309 --> 17:40.032
The second is equally important.

17:40.293 --> 17:41.775
Love your neighbor as yourself.

17:42.116 --> 17:45.202
No other commandment is greater than these.

17:47.170 --> 17:52.758
See, when Jesus gave us the great commandment, He didn't just give us an idea to contemplate.

17:52.798 --> 17:53.880
Again, it's not ethereal.

17:54.060 --> 17:56.484
He gave us a practical command to live out.

17:56.504 --> 18:02.853
When He says, love your neighbor as yourself, He's calling us to a deep personal investment.

18:04.416 --> 18:07.901
The word neighbor isn't just a metaphor for people in general.

18:08.021 --> 18:14.951
It literally means the person living next to you, the one whose home is closest to yours.

18:15.632 --> 18:16.754
But how do we

18:16.898 --> 18:19.881
actually think about our neighbors this way.

18:20.982 --> 18:24.946
How often do we go beyond a hey neighbor or a nod?

18:26.547 --> 18:32.132
How often do we take time to genuinely know and love the people in our immediate vicinity?

18:33.934 --> 18:37.638
Because again, it's not an ethereal ideology.

18:39.479 --> 18:45.465
It is a literal command to love your neighbors.

18:45.485 --> 18:46.546
So let's go a little deeper.

18:51.106 --> 18:57.354
I want to go back to the story that we discussed in the introduction about the Pastor Mark and planning the big family day.

18:57.834 --> 19:01.439
Despite all of the preparation and effort, only a few people showed up.

19:02.120 --> 19:04.963
But right down the street, the local park was packed.

19:06.004 --> 19:06.946
What was the difference?

19:08.227 --> 19:15.276
The people were already gathering in a place where they felt connected and where they felt known.

19:16.217 --> 19:16.978
This is key.

19:20.226 --> 19:36.630
This is a reminder that when it comes to loving our neighbors, if we want them to come to our events at our church, if we want them to come to our worship services, then we may miss the opportunities of the people that are right next door if we're trying to wait for them to come.

19:36.911 --> 19:43.721
There used to be a day back a couple of decades ago, the phrase, anybody remember the movie Field of Dreams?

19:43.941 --> 19:45.484
I know I'm dating myself a little bit.

19:45.564 --> 19:47.467
Kevin Costner, amen.

19:47.487 --> 19:49.810
Thank you sister for not leaving me out by myself.

19:52.066 --> 19:55.470
He felt like he was told to build this baseball field.

19:56.231 --> 20:00.536
And the voice told him, if you build it, they will come.

20:01.337 --> 20:02.879
Because it was out in the middle of a corn field.

20:03.400 --> 20:06.143
Who's gonna come out in the middle of a corn field to watch a ball game?

20:08.186 --> 20:10.508
And in the story, he built it and they came.

20:11.690 --> 20:13.432
That's not church, okay?

20:14.073 --> 20:16.516
There used to be a day when the church was like that.

20:16.836 --> 20:21.682
You would build the building, you'd put the sign out, people would come and worship.

20:22.050 --> 20:27.496
Because by and large, the mindset was you go to church on Sunday, even if you were at the bar on Saturday.

20:27.736 --> 20:28.757
Kind of didn't really matter.

20:29.418 --> 20:31.480
Everybody was a little bit biblically literate.

20:31.581 --> 20:35.605
Everybody was a little bit understanding of Christian terms and terminology.

20:36.626 --> 20:38.668
But if you built it, people would come.

20:40.210 --> 20:41.151
That's not the case today.

20:42.873 --> 20:48.479
Again, we talk a lot about this, but people don't care how much you know until they know how much you care.

20:48.980 --> 20:50.962
They want to know that you know their name.

20:51.458 --> 20:53.302
You're not just trying to fill the pew.

20:53.603 --> 21:02.403
You're not just trying to get somebody to come in so you can check it off your little church attendance box so that at the end of the year you get best volunteer at church award.

21:02.463 --> 21:10.802
They want to know that you're asking them because you care about them as an individual, as a person.

21:14.850 --> 21:27.344
A survey found that 30% of Americans don't know any of their neighbors and only 20% of people actually spend time regularly with those in their actual neighborhood.

21:29.867 --> 21:32.069
So how do we put this into practice?

21:32.089 --> 21:40.018
Loving our neighbor means more than just hoping that they'll show up at our church events, our worship services or whatever our next outreach program is.

21:40.339 --> 21:43.442
It means that meeting them where they are

21:43.554 --> 21:45.696
in their homes, in their everyday lives.

21:46.117 --> 21:48.580
This is where small groups comes in, friends.

21:51.663 --> 21:55.107
You go, well, how do we do outreach?

21:55.127 --> 22:02.475
Invite your neighbors over, say, hey, listen, I know you probably won't come to church, but would you come over to my house on Thursday night for coffee?

22:02.915 --> 22:06.119
And we do this kind of this little Bible study thing.

22:06.379 --> 22:07.180
We watch a video.

22:09.322 --> 22:11.465
And we have videos for you to watch.

22:11.705 --> 22:12.786
I don't know if you know that or not.

22:13.442 --> 22:20.072
Okay, we have videos that you can use in your homes to show.

22:21.334 --> 22:24.159
All you have to do is call and ask, and I'll be happy to get you connected to them.

22:26.422 --> 22:29.086
But hey, would you come over and do a little Bible set?

22:29.106 --> 22:31.230
Well, okay, I mean, I guess that'd be all right.

22:31.250 --> 22:31.951
I don't wanna go to church.

22:32.271 --> 22:33.132
Yeah, we're not going to church.

22:34.915 --> 22:39.943
And all of a sudden, you've got two or three people come into your house, and they're coming every Thursday night, and guess what?

22:40.764 --> 22:41.906
You're doing evangelism.

22:42.530 --> 22:48.936
And now you've got a small group and you're discipling people who've still not yet stepped foot in to bury a temple yet.

22:50.057 --> 22:56.323
Keyword yet, because if you were discipling them and discipling them well, that would be a next logical step.

23:00.547 --> 23:06.793
How many of us can honestly say we know more than just the names of the people who live closest to us?

23:08.695 --> 23:09.576
Do we know their struggles?

23:09.636 --> 23:12.178
Do we know their hopes, their dreams, their fears?

23:13.378 --> 23:14.640
Have we let them know ours?

23:16.123 --> 23:18.126
Do they know our story, our background?

23:18.427 --> 23:19.929
Do they know that we're a Christian?

23:23.615 --> 23:33.572
I don't know, do you put a Christian flag out on your front porch or do you put a cross in your yard or is it just, you know, happy Easter or Jesus is alive at Easter or whatever it may be?

23:34.414 --> 23:36.978
Again, our story, our sermon today,

23:37.250 --> 23:44.320
Our series is loosely based on the book called The Art of Neighboring, and I've got a few little quotes to kind of share with it throughout it.

23:45.742 --> 23:46.743
One of them, it says this.

23:46.763 --> 23:55.856
It says, it's important for us to think about how we can go to the places where they, the people, our neighbors already are.

23:56.857 --> 23:59.261
It's a simple but profound insight.

24:01.504 --> 24:05.810
It causes us to rethink our approach to outreach and evangelism.

24:07.298 --> 24:18.431
Instead of always asking our neighbors to come with us, maybe, just maybe we should be going with them into their spaces and into their lives.

24:20.033 --> 24:23.437
Because sometimes that means going into places we don't particularly like.

24:24.438 --> 24:27.722
I have a pastor friend of mine and this is just kind of off the side a little bit.

24:28.142 --> 24:31.406
I have a pastor friend of mine that regularly goes with people to the bar.

24:32.527 --> 24:33.288
They're not Christians.

24:33.889 --> 24:34.930
He's not expecting a

24:35.106 --> 24:36.968
a non-Christian to act like a Christian.

24:37.269 --> 24:42.555
He doesn't drink, he orders a soda, but it gives him a chance to just talk.

24:43.236 --> 24:55.911
And he has reached more men that have now attended his church that way than ever holding an outreach event or anything out in the community, or here at the church building, sorry.

24:57.173 --> 25:01.598
Because he's willing to go to the places that we don't normally like to go to.

25:02.439 --> 25:05.042
He's willing to get down and dirty and into the mess

25:12.418 --> 25:17.524
See, when we talk about loving our neighbor, it's about meeting them where they are.

25:18.285 --> 25:24.393
It's about being what we need to be to them, not asking them to be something for us.

25:28.518 --> 25:30.761
Because there's a danger in neglecting our neighbor.

25:31.421 --> 25:41.714
There's a danger in leaving them out or ignoring them and only being in our little circle of church people and church life.

25:45.154 --> 25:57.428
1 Peter 4.8 tells us that most of important of all continue to show deep love for each other, for love covers a multitude of sins.

26:02.053 --> 26:09.022
So of course, again, when we talk about loving our literal neighbors, there's our passage.

26:10.663 --> 26:12.946
When we talk about loving our literal neighbors,

26:14.306 --> 26:21.537
That's easy to say, but of course it begs the question, who is my neighbor?

26:26.264 --> 26:31.832
We spoke last week about the Good Samaritan and the parable of what that is.

26:31.852 --> 26:41.266
I want you to think back again, because this is a response to a lawyer's question.

26:43.010 --> 26:48.105
A lawyer is asking Jesus this question of who is my neighbor.

26:50.873 --> 26:52.217
And this is Jesus' response.

26:52.237 --> 26:56.690
He says, a man is traveling from Jerusalem to Jericho.

26:57.218 --> 26:59.200
a dangerous road known for bandits.

26:59.220 --> 27:02.124
He's attacked, robbed, and left for dead on the side of the road.

27:02.164 --> 27:07.189
Two religious leaders, a priest, and a Levite both see him, but choose to pass on the other side.

27:07.690 --> 27:13.236
These were men who, by their positions, were expected to know and follow the commandments.

27:13.837 --> 27:18.722
Yet they failed to act when confronted with a clear opportunity to love their neighbor.

27:21.406 --> 27:25.330
And again, as we spoke before, we often find ourselves in very similar position.

27:27.106 --> 27:28.528
We encounter people in need.

27:29.809 --> 27:35.556
We might even justify our inaction by thinking, well, they're not my responsibility.

27:35.856 --> 27:37.077
Somebody else will help them.

27:37.958 --> 27:44.986
But Jesus is parable, tells us that our neighbor is not defined by proximity, race, or social standing.

27:45.747 --> 27:51.594
Our neighbor is anyone in need of whom God places in our path.

27:51.614 --> 27:55.538
So our neighbor is both the person literally next door

27:56.482 --> 28:01.192
and the people that are farther away, the people that God places in our path.

28:03.537 --> 28:14.441
Again, in the book, The Art of Neighboring, they say this, it says, the man, the lawyer from our passage, wanted to define this word neighbor in such a way that he could not be found blameworthy.

28:14.942 --> 28:16.946
Isn't that like most of us?

28:17.570 --> 28:20.413
Lord, I want you to define something for me.

28:20.693 --> 28:38.734
I need you to explain something because what we're not really looking for the explanation, what we're really looking for is where are the lines and how close to the line can I get without falling off, without crossing it, so that I can still say I didn't actually do it.

28:41.096 --> 28:42.418
And the lawyer's looking for that.

28:42.458 --> 28:46.322
He's looking for the line, how he can

28:46.722 --> 28:54.755
be blameless, but still basically ignore the people that Jesus is trying to get us to care for.

28:58.120 --> 29:02.848
See, for most of us, we need to expand our borders and push past our comfort zones.

29:04.511 --> 29:13.906
And while it might be easy to redefine neighbors that we like and love, but what about loving neighbors that we dislike?

29:15.394 --> 29:20.340
See, the parable that Jesus tells goes on to describe the hero of the story as Samaritan.

29:21.121 --> 29:26.707
For Jesus' Jewish audience, this would have been a shocking tale.

29:27.988 --> 29:29.710
Samaritans were despised by the Jews.

29:29.750 --> 29:37.840
There was deep-seated animosity between these two groups, yet it was the Samaritan, not the religious leaders who showed compassion.

29:38.180 --> 29:43.506
He stopped, he tended to the man's wounds, and he ensured he was cared for until he recovered.

29:44.386 --> 29:47.870
The Samaritan's actions went on beyond basic help.

29:48.591 --> 29:50.573
He showed sacrificial love.

29:54.778 --> 30:08.914
See, this kind of points for us to love the people that we might naturally avoid or to love the people that maybe even

30:09.410 --> 30:14.437
harbor animosity towards us or that we might be harboring animosity toward.

30:18.062 --> 30:20.626
Maybe there's somebody in your life who's hurt you.

30:20.666 --> 30:23.150
Maybe you find it difficult to love.

30:25.033 --> 30:29.980
It could be a co-worker, a family member, or even a neighbor with whom you've had some kind of disagreement.

30:31.462 --> 30:37.170
Jesus calls us to love even those people to cross cultural and personal boundaries

30:38.498 --> 30:39.459
Just like the Samaritan did.

30:40.741 --> 30:43.785
This is a practical application for us.

30:46.008 --> 30:51.155
See, Jesus' point was that the Samaritan was actually the true neighbor.

30:52.737 --> 30:59.986
It wasn't the people going, look at me, look how holy I am, look how righteous I am, look at all the things that I do for God.

31:00.866 --> 31:08.378
Look at how wonderful I give my penance every Sunday at church and I put it in the box for the homeless or the needy.

31:08.618 --> 31:10.541
Look at all these great things that I do.

31:10.762 --> 31:12.144
It wasn't those people.

31:12.284 --> 31:18.173
It was the Samaritan who actually put it into action.

31:20.096 --> 31:23.602
And this kind of flips our understanding of what love is on its head.

31:32.706 --> 31:34.709
Sorry, get me through these.

31:34.729 --> 31:43.923
I think I missed my, no, here we go.

31:46.848 --> 31:56.042
Matthew 5, 43, and 44 says, you've heard the loss that says, love your neighbor and hate your enemy, but I say love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you.

31:57.184 --> 31:58.225
So what is our function?

31:59.007 --> 32:01.170
For the people that we might not like,

32:01.698 --> 32:10.472
For the people that might scare us, I reference often because in our American society, they've kind of demonized these guys a lot.

32:10.813 --> 32:12.436
It's the big burly biker guys.

32:13.297 --> 32:28.402
When most of them are about as sweet and nice as a teddy bear that you could ever meet, good-hearted American loving guys, they just have lots of tattoos and their muscles are bigger than my head.

32:31.426 --> 32:35.114
But the reality is, we've kind of demonized them.

32:35.214 --> 32:41.988
We've made shows like Sons of Anarchy, and we've made shows like, well, there's all kinds of them out there, and they always play the big, tough, bad guy.

32:44.454 --> 32:46.578
But the reality is,

32:48.162 --> 33:01.535
We can love those guys just as well as we can love the businessman who's in a shirt and tie and is, you know, is well-spoken and eloquent and able to act and treat as nice and great as it could be.

33:04.598 --> 33:09.023
We're called to love whomever to act on that love.

33:12.406 --> 33:16.530
Third thing, there we go.

33:16.930 --> 33:28.604
when we talk about loving our neighbor, when we talk about putting the great commandment into action, being serious about it, is moving the great commandment from theory to practice.

33:28.644 --> 33:29.545
And how do we do that?

33:30.746 --> 33:33.910
Again, this is kind of a rubber meets the road kind of a message.

33:34.491 --> 33:43.922
James chapter two and verse 14 through 17 says, what good is it, dear brothers and sisters, if you say you have faith, but don't show it by your actions.

33:44.002 --> 33:46.025
Can this kind of faith save anyone?

33:46.405 --> 33:53.514
Suppose you see a brother or a sister who has no food or clothing, and you say, goodbye, have a good day, stay warm, and eat well.

33:54.075 --> 33:57.279
But then you don't give that person any food or clothing.

33:57.399 --> 33:59.202
What good does that do?

34:00.524 --> 34:04.028
So you see, by faith, by itself isn't enough.

34:04.308 --> 34:08.594
Unless it produces good deeds, it's dead and useless.

34:11.074 --> 34:17.323
Now we could spend a whole nother message breaking down to just this passage and breaking down exactly what it means.

34:17.663 --> 34:18.685
But the point is this.

34:22.330 --> 34:29.781
Jesus gives us a great commandment to love the Lord with all of our heart, soul and strength and to love our neighbor as ourselves.

34:31.523 --> 34:36.210
James makes it clear when he says faith without deeds is dead.

34:37.762 --> 34:44.169
Our love for our neighbor can't remain in the realm of good intentions or just theoretical discussions.

34:44.229 --> 34:47.233
It has to be expressed through concrete action.

34:48.854 --> 34:52.779
So you remember we passed out the little slips of paper.

34:52.819 --> 34:53.840
Does everybody have one?

34:55.622 --> 35:00.628
Everybody have wave your paper in the air because we really do care.

35:01.929 --> 35:02.650
Thank you.

35:02.670 --> 35:02.770
Okay.

35:10.338 --> 35:17.545
I want you to start thinking about your own personal neighborhood and the people that live around you.

35:18.526 --> 35:22.030
It's not just enough to believe we have to act on it.

35:24.892 --> 35:33.281
So in the art of neighboring, the authors propose an exercise to bring the great commandment into our real world.

35:35.082 --> 35:38.706
They call it the chart of shame and it's simple

35:39.010 --> 35:42.254
yet it is a convicting activity.

35:43.556 --> 35:44.998
And so we're gonna do it today.

35:45.018 --> 35:52.388
I want you to take your slip of paper and I want you to draw a tic-tac-toe board on it.

35:52.408 --> 35:53.550
Do you know what I'm talking about?

35:53.970 --> 35:56.554
If you're young enough, they call it a hashtag.

35:58.116 --> 36:03.844
Or if you're a little on the older side and you remember the old phone, they call it the pound sign.

36:05.226 --> 36:08.370
It's line, line, line,

36:08.482 --> 36:10.785
line, you should have nine boxes.

36:12.127 --> 36:14.050
Okay, the X's and O's game.

36:16.694 --> 36:22.522
So if you have a pen or a pencil, make that symbol on your paper.

36:23.764 --> 36:31.375
It's just a tic-tac-toe board or a hashtag or a pound sign, whichever generation you identify with best.

36:31.655 --> 36:36.242
There should be some pens and pencils in your pews, hopefully, if they've not all disappeared.

36:40.418 --> 36:43.562
In the middle box, there should be one box that's in the center.

36:44.983 --> 36:46.765
I want you to write home.

36:50.089 --> 36:55.235
That represents your house where you physically live.

36:57.998 --> 36:59.860
And here's the challenge that I have for you.

37:01.522 --> 37:08.850
It's to fill in three pieces of information for each of the eight homes, the boxes around the edge,

37:10.114 --> 37:15.760
Fill in three pieces of relevant information about the people that live in those boxes.

37:16.181 --> 37:20.646
Something deeper like their hopes, their fears, their spiritual beliefs, something.

37:20.926 --> 37:24.490
Write their name and something about that neighbor.

37:24.991 --> 37:26.132
Go ahead, I'll wait.

37:32.339 --> 37:38.546
Something you know about three pieces though in every box, not just three little things individually.

37:39.906 --> 37:42.871
One right above you is the person who lives across the street from you.

37:43.913 --> 37:47.038
Their name and three pieces of information about them.

37:48.159 --> 37:51.244
The one next to it is the person who lives across the street catty corner from you.

37:52.667 --> 37:55.431
The one below is the person who lives behind you.

37:57.535 --> 38:04.466
Write their name and three pieces of information about that person in as many of the boxes as you can.

38:11.042 --> 38:13.426
So I see a few people looking up, quite a few still.

38:14.147 --> 38:15.890
It's not as easy as it seems, right?

38:19.756 --> 38:22.721
So why do they call this exercise the chart of shame?

38:24.163 --> 38:29.592
Well, because most people when they attempt this, find out that they know very little about their neighbors.

38:29.632 --> 38:38.066
In fact, only about 10% of people can fill out all three pieces of information for even one of their neighbors.

38:40.322 --> 38:49.236
and doing this little exercise exposes the gap between our intentions to love our neighbors and our actual engagement with them.

38:49.536 --> 38:51.980
If I had to guess, every one of you in here are Christians.

38:52.301 --> 38:55.566
Every one of you says that you have the love of Jesus, and guess what?

38:55.866 --> 38:56.507
I believe that.

38:58.430 --> 39:02.617
Every one of us, I believe, intends to love our neighbor as ourselves.

39:02.877 --> 39:03.118
Why?

39:03.178 --> 39:04.520
Because Jesus asks us to.

39:04.800 --> 39:05.662
That is our heart.

39:05.742 --> 39:08.466
I believe every person within the sound of my voice

39:08.546 --> 39:13.113
truly wants to fulfill the great commandment and the great commission.

39:13.493 --> 39:25.211
But there is a gap between the desire to do it and the practical everyday action of actually doing it.

39:28.936 --> 39:34.865
See, if we don't take Jesus' command literally, then we turn the great commandment into nothing more than a metaphor.

39:35.907 --> 39:36.948
It's just an ideology.

39:36.988 --> 39:38.130
It's a cute story.

39:40.354 --> 39:45.179
We talked last week about overcoming some of the obstacles, busyness.

39:45.640 --> 39:53.028
We talked about things like busy schedules or the fences that are between our houses, the walls that literally stand between us.

39:53.408 --> 40:00.376
There's also the things like fear and distrust or simply the discomfort of stepping out of our comfort zone.

40:00.416 --> 40:06.002
For some of us who are introverts, it's not really natural for us to just jump out and talk to somebody.

40:12.930 --> 40:15.934
We've got to move in the great commandment.

40:15.954 --> 40:17.676
We've got to move it from theory to practice.

40:19.598 --> 40:23.263
Romans 12 and verse 10 says, love each other with genuine affection.

40:23.664 --> 40:25.966
Take delight in honoring each other.

40:25.986 --> 40:38.322
70% of people say they'd like to know their neighbors better, but most cite busyness as their primary obstacle.

40:40.898 --> 40:42.800
There's all kinds of things that stand in the way.

40:45.143 --> 40:49.367
There's all kinds of things that are getting in the way of us trying to know who our neighbor is.

40:51.229 --> 40:53.011
And how do we become a good neighbor?

40:53.091 --> 41:02.061
How do we become a church that offers hope and healing to our community, to our neighborhood by being a good neighbor?

41:02.401 --> 41:05.184
How do we become that if we don't even know our neighbors?

41:06.846 --> 41:10.290
How do we become an instrument

41:10.370 --> 41:21.102
a catalyst, an ambassador for the King of Kings, if we don't even know the people that he sent us to serve.

41:25.067 --> 41:38.002
So as we close this morning, I want us to commit to moving from intention to action, from theory to practice, and from good ideas,

41:38.146 --> 41:39.909
to a real impact in our neighborhoods.

41:40.270 --> 41:44.779
If you want to see Berea Temple full, meet your neighbors.

41:46.843 --> 41:56.401
If you want to see the church filled with people, we have to get out of our homes because they're not just going to come.

41:56.421 --> 41:58.285
We're in a day and age, unfortunately.

41:59.427 --> 42:00.850
They're not just going to show up.

42:02.274 --> 42:09.390
We as individuals have to get outside the four walls of our homes, outside the four walls of our church, and get out into the marketplace.

42:15.523 --> 42:17.367
So how do we respond to a message like this?

42:18.028 --> 42:22.418
Because this is more of a practical action type of a sermon.

42:24.418 --> 42:34.529
See, the truth is it's not just about gaining the knowledge of how to be a good neighbor, but it's about the transformation that needs to happen in every one of our hearts, mine included.

42:36.391 --> 42:42.077
It's about allowing the love of God to flow through us into the lives of those around us.

42:43.659 --> 42:45.501
Listen, your neighbors might scare you.

42:46.902 --> 42:48.864
Your neighbors might be your best friend.

42:51.927 --> 42:54.290
But we have an obligation to love them.

42:55.266 --> 42:57.149
Because it's not going to happen by accident.

42:58.611 --> 43:03.859
It requires intentionality, effort, and willingness to step out of our comfort zones.

43:11.751 --> 43:13.433
Take the slip of paper that you had.

43:13.473 --> 43:16.037
Worship team, I know you don't have them.

43:16.057 --> 43:18.701
It's OK. Just hold on to it for a moment.

43:18.821 --> 43:19.723
You don't have to hold it up.

43:19.743 --> 43:21.345
But just hold on to that slip of paper.

43:22.226 --> 43:24.029
It might have some neighbor's names on it.

43:24.089 --> 43:24.690
It might not.

43:26.882 --> 43:33.281
But I want to challenge each of us to take one concrete step this week to fill in those boxes.

43:34.986 --> 43:39.058
Maybe it's just getting to know one of those neighbors.

43:40.482 --> 43:49.837
Maybe it's making a plan to connect with a neighbor you don't know very well, or maybe it's reaching out to a neighbor that you've had a strained relationship with, and offering an olive branch.

43:50.138 --> 44:00.274
Or maybe it's simply being more present in your neighborhood, taking walks, starting conversation, being available to those who might need a listening ear or a helping hand.

44:06.114 --> 44:11.381
Galatians chapter 5 and verse 14 says, for the whole law can be summed up in this one command.

44:11.421 --> 44:13.605
Love your neighbors yourself.

44:17.570 --> 44:23.799
So Father, I pray, I pray over this congregation.

44:23.819 --> 44:28.786
Father, I pray that you would begin to burn a love for our neighbor inside each one of us.

44:31.170 --> 44:34.054
Father, if there's strange relationships, I pray for healing.

44:34.134 --> 44:40.344
If there's people that need to have reconciliation, I pray that you would bring that, Father.

44:43.228 --> 44:49.497
Father, I pray that you would help Maria Temple be a place where people find hope and healing.

44:49.517 --> 44:51.360
Because good neighbors stepped out.

44:52.382 --> 44:57.249
Stepped out of their comfort zone and out of the four walls of their homes and of their church.

44:57.269 --> 45:00.594
And they met people where they are.

45:03.042 --> 45:09.959
They were willing to go to the hard places and to have hard conversations.

45:10.782 --> 45:12.225
Father, do a mighty work.

45:13.950 --> 45:15.714
We praise You, and we thank You.

45:15.734 --> 45:17.298
It's in the name of Jesus, we pray.

45:18.200 --> 45:19.163
Amen.

45:20.366 --> 45:20.466
Amen.

